Product description

We identified a significant need among League of Legends players for accessible and effective user-tailored tools to enhance their skill levels and macro awareness. As a result, we aim to develop a complimentary third-party software solution that empowers players to learn and progress without any cost. We would like to do so post-game by accessing the replay files with Riot's developer tools and providing users with a custom and interactive way to navigate through their past games, with advice. We also have plans of hiring high-elo players to give professional advice to the users. We genuinely hope that this product can contribute to fostering a more positive and encouraging environment for League of Legends players, where everyone is motivated to learn and enhance their own skills.

Software Implementation


Figure 1. Flowchart Replay Academy¡¯s flow of actions

 

UI demo

The UI of the product will be very simple. After logging in to the LoL client, the APP/webpage of Replay Academy will automatically load the user¡¯s ID and match history and display them like the following:

Here the user can pick one of the matches and expand it to see the detailed information and load the replay file. Then, after the replay file is processed, a new page with in-game view will be displayed:

Here the analysed mistakes done by the user will be marked on the time axis and the user can skip to that part directly. When the user clicks the marked mistake, a text box will appear on screen with the explanation of the mistake and the corresponding advice. We will also add tools for players to put their own landmarks and comments to the replay. We also aim to make the software listen during games for a specific command (i.e. CTRL+S) to save a checkpoint in the middle of the game that the user will later be able to refer to on the Replay Academy app.

Example algorithms

Below you will find a list of 4 example algorithms that will be used to flag player¡¯s mistakes. The ultimate goal is to make a complete tool, which would have many more algorithms for mistake/misplay detection. When implementing the software, intensive testing would be done on labelled replays to validate and fine-tune our algorithms.

 

 

Eg1. Early, middle and late game performance of each champ will be extracted. Then, overall game play advice will be evaluated accordingly. For example, if the user¡¯s team have a Kayle top, mid Kassadin and bot Jinx with Lulu, the evaluated game play should be to scale/avoid fights. If the user played too aggressively or forced unnecessary fights/skirmishes, the move will be marked as a mistake on the time axis.

 

Eg2. When lane swaps happen, some players don¡¯t choose to go to an empty lane and farm but go to an occupied lane instead and cause an overall gold and EXP loss, which is noticeable in the replay. When this happens, the move will be marked as a mistake and advice will be given for the player to improve.

 

Eg3. Many algorithms to guide wave management will be implemented. An example algorithm would take a toplaner's matchup statistics as well as the current gold/exp advantage and relative position of the minions. Suppose a lvl 3 Riven is against a lvl 2 Kayle and the riven player hard pushes, this would be flagged as a mistake as slow pushing could result in multiple benefits such as a possible successful dive, a slower bounceback and a higher minion loss on Kayle's part.

 

Eg.4 Objective-based algorithms will be implemented. Let's take an example for drake objective as a midlaner. This algorithm would know the matchup statistics at the specific minute, the current state of the lane gold/exp wise, the position of ally jungler and botlane and the current relative minion position in midlane. Suppose the drake is up and the botlane and jungler are close by to the drake. If the midlane player is allowed to push (matchup advantage wise), but decides to freeze, this would be flagged as a mistake, as it would be more advantageous for the player to hard or slow push and gain roaming priority for the drake objective.
